Description: Record the requested resolution on virtual-monitor screencast streams.
 .
 ``Screencasting::createVirtualMonitorStream`` forgot to assign
 ``stream->d->m_size`` after constructing the new
 ``ScreencastingStream``, while the sibling ``createRegionStream``
 (and ``createOutputStream`` via ``QScreen::virtualSize()``) both do
 set it from their respective inputs. As a result, every consumer
 that later calls ``stream->size()`` on a virtual-monitor stream gets
 a default-constructed (invalid) ``QSize`` back.
 .
 The most visible victim is ``PlasmaScreencastV1Session::start()``,
 which on the ``ScreencastingStream::created`` signal copies that
 size into the abstract session's logical size:
 .
     setLogicalSize(d->request->size());
 .
 The logical size is then used by ``sendEvent()`` to scale incoming
 mouse coordinates from the pipewire stream's pixel space to wayland
 logical coordinates:
 .
     auto logicalPosition = QPointF{
         (position.x() / size().width())  * logicalSize().width(),
         (position.y() / size().height()) * logicalSize().height(),
     };
     d->remoteInterface->pointer_motion_absolute(
         logicalPosition.x(), logicalPosition.y());
 .
 With ``logicalSize()`` returning an invalid ``QSize``, the right-hand
 multiplications are zero (or negative one, depending on Qt's default
 ``QSize`` value across versions), and every remote pointer event is
 sent as ``pointer_motion_absolute(0.0, 0.0)``. The cursor on the
 KWin side ends up pinned to the top-left of the screen, which on a
 default Plasma desktop is the upper-left hot corner -- the trigger
 for the Overview ("Present Windows") effect. That makes the symptom
 *very* spectacular when an mstsc user moves the mouse: the cursor
 appears to jump to the corner repeatedly, Overview keeps activating,
 and clicks land on whatever ends up under (0,0) (or nothing at all),
 which mostly means clicks are silently dropped.
 .
 The fix is a one-line analogue of the assignment in
 ``createRegionStream``: store the resolution we just asked the
 compositor for, so that downstream callers get a sensible size.
 The dpr argument is intentionally not folded into m_size: m_size is
 documented as the logical (device-independent) extent of the stream
 and the dpr is reported separately if a caller needs it.
